Subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="ECB4B2457C85DC8B05189F6B8FD66EDA" LSID="2820DE66-DF24-57E3-9F07-CC41A2218458" authority="LeConte, 1851" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Diaphorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="(Thalpius)" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Thalpius">Thalpius LeConte, 1851</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FB8F2C374890E28215A7F967F191739C" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="23E05F9822B003BEFF3391953BF6DFE0" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">
<taxonomicName id="7E55DB9A50628AF93999E7E96F4BBCC3" authorityName="Leconte" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Thalpius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Thalpius</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1851: 174. Type species: 
<taxonomicName id="A19589494937A667464AD1F1827F7503" authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1826" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Helluo" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaeus">
<emphasis id="DECCC2D857D15823BA2EA0DD92BA5ECE" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Helluo pygmaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1826 by monotypy. Etymology. Probably from the Greek 
<emphasis id="969132F935F3088D480BC0B16CE793A4" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">thalpos</emphasis>
(warmth, heat), possibly alluding to the climatic region where the sole species then known lived [masculine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A5B75BE585732BF31689EA1E282E1794" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">
<taxonomicName id="912E9E423481816EE6CFB25673C3DD48" authorityName="Leconte" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Enaphorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Enaphorus</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1851: 174. Type species: 
<taxonomicName id="43F5B5651F96D462C6AEFFCA60C83F72" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Enaphorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufulus">
<emphasis id="CD668BBA59A0BCC0332D6FB429E7EB85" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Enaphorus rufulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1851 by monotypy. Synonymy established by LeConte (1853c: 373).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA152D8CC549CCDBC2CDB7DD7C6F5C9C" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">
<taxonomicName id="FFFD8583188C23E3E5B94DDB3D2B2104" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1868" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Zuphiosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zuphiosoma</taxonomicName>
Laporte, 1867: 103. Type species: 
<taxonomicName id="D50FE06C1AB2AA56865DABB7C3BD86F1" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Zuphiosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulva">
<emphasis id="C29389174F8120FC0FB249DCE85DA25B" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Zuphiosoma fulva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Laporte, 1867 by monotypy. Synonymy established by Csiki (1932b: 1561). Etymology. From the generic name 
<taxonomicName id="541F88075523D96779A224F0463218B4" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1805" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Zuphium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8C9E504448057E18BD18B3373D89620F" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Zuphium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<emphasis id="727B4C0FDE07A7CC04AFF8D5926E38F4" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">q.v</emphasis>
.] and the Greek 
<emphasis id="1A4451FBEAC04EC1B62C1AF4B6D47B67" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">soma</emphasis>
(body) [neuter].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FD8E5427BD9E0A9A955CCA1150625B73" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" type="diversity">
<paragraph id="4D35B87EE9559B0DF5012AF7B78ED060" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FEFEA63C24D5AEFAEC44DABC0DC1B66E" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Thirty-four species (Lorenz 2005: 505) in the Nearctic (nine species but only two endemic), Neotropical (23 species), and Australian (nine species in Australia) Regions.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="724D8D6588D818554D14A552CF67646F" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" type="identification">
<paragraph id="0F56F202A165523E411B091976EC3F9E" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="490DC46003D54CAD0697DB582754DCA5" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Messer (2011: 422-423) published a key to all species found in the United States and Mexico.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7E2FAEEDE80BC2485EAE34C7C73B6211" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" type="taxonomic note">
<paragraph id="922B896D99F696371F07C89A6F7C6DB5" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Taxonomic Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BAD7909B7688D91D00BEEBA892C6B3AA" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">
This taxon is considered as a distinct genus by some authors (e.g., Ball and Bousquet 2000: 115) but Baehr (1985: 36) found out that the character states between 
<taxonomicName id="7F052EF3F144B542901451AEE21E60C9" authorityName="Leconte" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Thalpius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EC18187C8DB81D7E3708DCA8CDD4EAEB" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Thalpius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="448B36FC6D910BF055E2E8AEE0DEFAF4" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1834" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Pseudaptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2E190B4F2E3B4B1AE2FEEA3CF729B9B0" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Pseudaptinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were &quot;very few and rather weak.&quot; I am following him and treat 
<taxonomicName id="CF0EB9641999B21F7F5E1D15A02D97A1" authorityName="Leconte" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Thalpius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EAD812803E3B3DB3976A80DBD382F6A6" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Thalpius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName id="D2C06BBEF2E9B9638AADBC9FAE166C11" authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1834" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Pseudaptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="837" pageNumber="838" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="037E4ECB492EFD55AA0F35F54EF45959" italics="true" pageId="837" pageNumber="838">Pseudaptinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
